<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-446-060  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 446 060.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 14 1990 v7 n19 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Adobe assembles PostScript battery: new controllers to pave wayfor low-cost printers. (Adobe Systems Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bernard, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Adobe Systems Inc is at work on a set of products intended to wincustomers from competing graphics printers by lowering the pricesof high-performance PostScript printers.andP;  A line of PostScriptcontrollers will be based on processors from NationalSemiconductor Corp, Intel Corp and Weitek Corp. NationalSemiconductor will, in May 1990, release a chip that combinesPostScript, scanning, and fax capabilities.andP;  Adobe plans to sellthe controllers to such printer makers as Ricoh Corp and CanonUSA, which is expected to produce a hybrid printer/fax machineusing National Semi's chip.andP;  The PostScript page descriptionlanguage will also be rewritten.andP;  PostScript Level 2 will offerimproved memory management, support for Japanese kanji characters,m and enhanced color.andP;  It is due out in Jun 1990.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Adobe Systems Inc. (product development).andO;Topic:     Page Description LanguagesProduct DevelopmentControllersPriceLaser printers.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   PostScript printer prices 1985-1990. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Diane BernardandM;Adobe Systems Inc. is building an arsenal of new PostScript products to wardoff graphics printer competitors and eventually bring usershigher-performance PostScript printing at lower prices.andM;The company's product plans include a major rewrite of its page-descriptionlanguage and a family of PostScript controllers based on new third-partyprocessors from Weitek Corp., National Semiconductor Corp. and Intel Corp.,andO;according to Pat Marriott, director of marketing at Adobe in Mountain View,Calif.andP;  Adobe will sell the controllers to printer makers such as CanonU.S.A.andP;  Inc., NEC Technologies Inc. and Ricoh Corp., she said.andM;&quot;Within the next 18 months, Adobe's goal is to offer OEMs a range ofcontrollers to bring users PostScript printers for under $1,000,&quot; Marriottsaid.andM;In addition to lowering prices, Adobe hopes to boost the capability ofPostScript printers with its controllers and revamped software, sources said.andM;National Semiconductor next week plans to launch the first of a new family ofPostScript chips that combine PostScript printing with fax and scannercapabilities, sources said.andM;Canon, Olivetti U.S.A.andP;  and Samsung Information Systems America Inc. areexpected by fall to use an Adobe controller that incorporates the NationalSemiconductor chip as the basis of a new breed of hybrid PostScript printersthat also serve as fax machines, sources said.andM;Weitek Corp. also plans to launch next week a PostScript processor thatofficials said offers four times the performance of its predecessor at almosthalf the cost.andM;Canon, NEC and Ricoh are expected to build printers based on an Adobe boardthat uses the Weitek controller, according to sources.andM;Not to be outdone, Intel is working to enhance PostScript's colorcapabilities with its i960 processor.andP;  By fall, vendors including Canon areexpected to introduce color PostScript printers based on the i960 that willcost about $5,000, according to Alan Steinberg, marketing manager at Intel'sPersonal Computer Enhancement Operation in Hillsboro, Ore.andM;Further boosting PostScript capabilities, Adobe plans to release next monthPostScript Level 2, a major rewrite of the language that offers enhancedcolor, better memory management and support for Japanese kanji characters,according to Marriott.andP;  The company will unveil the update at its firstdevelopers conference June 3-5 in San Jose, Calif.andM;To top it off, Adobe plans to offer off-the-shelf PostScript software thatcan be run on PCs to produce PostScript output on non-PostScript printers.andO;The software will be priced competitively with similar packages that costless than $500, such as QMS Inc.'s UltraScript and Custom Applications Inc.'sFreedom of Press, sources said.andM;&quot;Adobe's taking a proactive role -- they're feeling competition and have toinundate the printer community with PostScript visibility and betterproducts,&quot; said Rob Auster, director of electronic printing at BIS CAPInternational in Norwell, Mass.andM;The company's major competition comes from Hewlett-Packard Co.'s LaserJet IIIprinter, which includes outline fonts on a par with PostScript fonts, andMicrosoft Corp.'s forthcoming TrueImage PostScript clone, according toAuster.andM;While Adobe gathers additional PostScript strength, Microsoft is not sittingstill, said Dan Steele, manager of Microsoft's printer business unit inRedmond, Wash.andP;  Microsoft is also working with chip makers to port TrueImageto fast processors, he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>